  "text": "How should these results be interpreted with respect to the hypothesis that the Ca 2 ϩ bowl is the physical locus of a high-affinity binding site(s) coupled to voltage activation of the channel? Perhaps it is too soon to tell. The D899A mutation, which has practically no effect on the Ca 2 ϩ dependence of gating but has a large effect on the 45 Ca 2 ϩ -binding signal, is a worrisome anomaly. The authors correctly argue that the structure of the Ca 2 ϩ bowl may be greatly distorted in the blot assay and may not be a true reflection of Ca 2 ϩ binding in the native channel. This may explain certain inconsistencies between assays of Ca 2 ϩ activation and Ca 2 ϩ binding. Likewise, mutated residues that affect the Ca 2 ϩ dependence of voltage gating need not be located directly within a Ca 2 ϩ -binding site to perturb this process. However, when taken together with the demonstration that chimeric insertion of a region containing the Ca 2 ϩ bowl confers Ca 2 ϩ sensitivity to the Slo3 Tail [CITATION_1] , the probability that all of these results are due to a coincidental allosteric effect on Ca 2 ϩ binding to a region that lies outside of the Ca 2 ϩ bowl seems rather remote.",
